social_posts.post_text: Lovely side of snow to go with our freezing temps. Winter, a welcome December guest in Vermont, is finally settling in. More snow is needed though (just in case Winter is reading this, which you know she totally is…. ) #welcomewinter #vermontlife

I'm doing a GIVEAWAY! Sign-up for my FREE Uber Frugal Month Group Challenge and you'll be entered to win: 1) a one-on-one basic financial consultation with me; 2) a spot in a UFM Mastermind Group; 3) a photo of my dog with with a nametag on her head with your name written on it (because who doesn't need that?!?).
🎄⛄🎄
The UFM is my free, 31-day, email-based money management bootcamp. Sign-up at the link in my bio by December 18th to be entered in the giveaway drawing!
🎄⛄🎄
The UFM is designed as a spending detox, but it goes way beyond that and delves into almost every aspect of how we relate to, and manage, our money.
🎄⛄🎄
Through this Challenge, we’re going to save money like nobody’s business (well, like our business, actually) and embark on a transformative journey to analyze the mechanics and mindset behind our spending. The UFM provides a re-set for the consumer carousel many of us get caught up in. It prompts you to think not only about where you’re spending your money, but why you’re spending it. 
🎄⛄🎄
Reforming your relationship with money isn’t just a question of spending less and saving more, it’s a question of performing a holistic reflection on your priorities and your emotional relationship to your money. The UFM guides you through this process. 
🎄⛄🎄
Yes of course I bought a monogrammed stocking for my dog. I'm frugal, not a monster 😂. #christmasinvermont
Sherbet sunrise on this morning’s hike. Likely my last hike without snowshoes as we batten the hatches tonight for an incoming blizzard. #hikeeveryday #winterinvermont
Blizzard day 1: climbing snow-covered trees, playing Qwirkle, observing a dog eat mountains of snow, retaining power and internet!!!

Blizzard day 2: dog is officially shorter than the snow, chickens are boycotting their outdoor run, snowshoes are required to leave the house, 22 inches on the ground, still snowing. #vermontlife #winterdream

We sacrificed one carrot and one crocheted hat for the perfect ensemble. Then I looked outside and realized the kids also ransacked my decorative hydrangea bush to supply the arms and mouth… I will point out we have approximately 8,674 sticks and branches littering our yard and only one decorative hydrangea bush… #vermontlife #winterwonderland

As we brace for the next storm, my gratitude for this wood stove remains constant. It warms our entire home—with style, might I add. I love that my husband harvested this wood himself from our forest. I love that my children are learning the art of stacking wood. I do not love that my dog licks the stove. We can’t have it all, people. Can’t have it all. #vermontbyvermonters #woodstove
The sun rising on our frosty Christmas Eve morn, heralding a day of promise and light. #christmasinthewoods #vermontlife #hikeeveryday

The kids were thrilled with their second-hand, garage sale-sourced, previously loved gifts. Proving once again that buying used just might be the real Christmas miracle 🤣. And now don’t mind me as I straighten and fold all the wrapping paper to use again next year. Also, props to Kidwoods who wrapped up some stuff from around the house to gift us. I remember doing that when I was her age and thinking it was THE cleverest gifting idea. Ever. I hope your holiday is merry, relaxing and inexpensive! #chickenornament from @robertandbirdie

The eyes of someone allowed to have their very own real candle at the Christmas Eve candlelight service. I am so thankful for our little church, our little one town and our little community. The banners above the altar say it all: Peace. Love. Hope. Joy.

There’s still time to join an Uber Frugal Month Mastermind Group! Money is something we’re not supposed to discuss and so many of us don’t. These groups are the place to discuss every single weird money question you have. These groups are the place to share every single money success you experience. These groups are where you’ll find camaraderie and support.
**
There’s no question too big or too small for the groups to address because, for most of us, our financial educations began after we became adults, after we made some serious financial missteps (anyone remember my story about overdrawing my checking account in my 20s?). We feel like we SHOULD know this stuff and SHOULD be able to manage our money and so we don’t ask for help. Let yourself off the hook and come join us.
**
These Groups Exist to Address:
❤️ The lack of community and support you feel on your financial journey.
😱 Emotional turmoil around money–or financial trauma–that has sabotaged your past efforts to improve your financial health.
🤑 Complicated family dynamics and history that make it intimidating to figure out how to change your approach to money.
👀 An inability to stick with the habits promoted by the Uber Frugal Month for the long-term.
📚 A fear that you’re the only person who doesn’t understand financial terminology & jargon.
🧠 Lack of clarity on your long-term goals and how your money might impact your future.
🤷 A disconnect between you and your partner/spouse about how money should be managed.
👎 Undesirable financial routines/expectations you’ve set up with your kids and want to change.
😬 Shame and guilt over not taking charge of your financial life sooner.
🤦‍♀️ Embarrassment over your lack of personal finance knowledge.
👏 How to create a sustainable money plan that you actually can–and will–follow. 
**
We’ll meet (on video) for 5 weeks starting January 2nd. Register at the link in my bio!
Viewing snow from the inside. Can be the best option when temperatures hover in single digits. #vermontlife

I was going to say, “the sun rising on 2023,” but then I realized that’s tomorrow. I am really on top of things, let me tell you... Regardless, this is a sun and it is rising. Plz enjoy. #vermontbyvermonters

Today’s the LAST day to sign-up for my free Uber Frugal Month Challenge AND your last chance to join a Mastermind Group (link in bio)! Frugal Hound would like you to know this is also the last day she’ll be wearing this ridiculous dog coat. While the UFM technically started yesterday, if you sign-up today you’ll receive the Day One and Day Two emails and be on track with the group for the rest of the month.
❄️❄️❄️
Reminder: this is not the Underwear Fang Monkey OR Unstoppable Ferocious Moth Challenge–although both of those sound like they have a lot to offer. This UFM will help you get better at money. And it’s not just about frugality or about being uber, it’s about how you relate to your money, what your money makes you FEEL and how you can chart a healthier, more productive financial future.
❄️❄️❄️
I don’t think money is the root of all evil, but I do think money is the root of a lot of our problems. And it doesn’t have to be that way. You too can have an informed, confident approach to your personal finances. ❄️❄️❄️The UFM is a month-long, FREE, email-based program I developed as a result of my own journey to financial awareness. It follows the steps I took (and still take) to understand my finances and feel enfranchised to make decisions about my future.
❄️❄️❄️
Today is also the final day to join a UFM Mastermind Group, which you can do at the link in my bio. Each of these small groups will meet once a week with me (on video) for the duration of the Challenge to workshop and discuss the UFM lessons. These groups will serve as frugal support networks to help you on your journey to more proactive relationship with your money.
❄️❄️❄️
Since money is typically a forbidden conversation topic, many of us go through life wondering if we’re doing the right thing with it. These groups are the place to talk about this forbidden topic. These groups are an outlet to vent your concerns and fears about your money. These groups are the place to share your financial victories. Come join us! #uberfrugalmonth #januarychallenge

Christmas is still all over our house. On every flat surface—also some slanted—and hanging from the walls. I love the warmth of twinkly lights and ornaments, of stockings and the nutcrackers I’ve performed hot-glue surgery on 8 times already this year. In retrospect, it might’ve been a mistake to let the kids dress the nutcrackers up and cart them around in doll strollers. I’ll wait as long as reasonable before packing it all away because everything is artificial and reusable. The tree itself just celebrated its 10th year. Unbound by the constraints of drying, brown needles, Christmas happens for at least 2 months in our home. How about in yours?
This good doggo got hiking booties for Christmas! Come see what else we bought last month… link in bio.
Hens don’t care about things like snow. Snow is immaterial in their quest for the best scraps, served up daily by Kidwoods. Hens would cut you for some leftover PB&J. #winterchickens #vermontlife

Ski season is here, with its requisite car trunk picnics and predictable hot cocoa spilled in laps. While yes, ski lift tickets and lessons are expensive, the whole endeavor doesn’t have to be. Littlewoods featured here in hand-me-down skis and boots, a hand-me-down helmet, thrift store coat and garage sale snow pants. I pack our food. I pack our cocoa and coffee. We ski at our local mountain at least three days a week using our season passes, purchased early bird at a discount. There are ways to frugalize even the most expensive activity. What are your tricks? #skitheeast #skiingwithkids #carpicnics #forthewin
My gingerbread house in the woods: the most welcome sight upon return from my daily pre-dawn hike. Gratitude is too simple a word, too basic a feeling. But it’s sort of like that, only more.
Extremely helpful snow day co-workers. Cannot emphasize enough how productive this team is.

And the littlest one is up the chairlift! Skiing as a family fills me with excitement, gratitude and a deep sense that we live in the right place. I am so thankful we get to do this together all the time. Like a dream come true, except with more whining  than expected in a dream…. #skiwithkids #vermontlife
The unreal blue of a post-storm sky. The very real wood that warms my home. The omnipresent snow that brings my family so much joy. #vermontbyvermonters #woodshed

What makes you feel rich? What allows you to believe you have enough? What enables you to step off the consumer carousel? One example from my week: taking a midday walk with a wonderful friend amid this indelible Vermont beauty. #simplejoys #vermontbyvermonters #thatskyisreal #nofilter
This kid has found a home on the slopes! Now, fingers crossed the snow holds out at least a few more weeks!!! #skivermont

A belated Valentine’s appreciation for this phenomenal husband of mine. Listening to him read to our children (with all the voices), watching him ski behind Littlewoods patiently encouraging her down the slope, seeing him plow the snow from our driveway in the early morning. All done with love, without complaint, for us. Gratitude doesn’t quite cover how I feel witnessing this. Abiding love, tender regard, thankfulness—maybe that starts to sum it up. Whatever the right words are, I am very, very lucky to be married to this man.
Ever wondered what I eat? Wonder no more!!! Today I bring you an exposé, a deep dive into what we eat, where we buy it, how we prepare it and how much we spent on it last year. In total! Link in bio!

One of the gifts of having young children is enrollment in an endless carousel of illness. We’ve been passing around a stomach bug for the last four weeks and now that it’s in remission, we’re kept company by a head cold. Annoying as ceaseless sickness is, it gives me a window into practicing gratitude. During Covid lockdowns, we were never sick. We didn’t have the chance to catch anyone else’s germs. Hermetically sealed, we were devoid of school, friends, rollicking dinner parties with toddlers smearing lasagna on selves and others. But I wouldn’t go back. I wouldn’t trade illness-free living for what we’re blessed with now: a warm and loving elementary school, vibrant and hilarious friends, a rich community life at church and in town, skiing, snowshoeing, play dates and germs. And when I feel well enough to hike, I get to appreciate this sunrise at the top of our land. I want to practice and embody gratitude, even when a child throws up in the middle of the night (it’s always the middle of the night) and I’m relegated to the couch and it seems there’ll never be a moment when all four of us are well. Because we are lucky enough to get sick, to catch germs, to be healthy enough to move around in the world. So remind me—if I complain—that this too is a privilege. #parentinginreallife #hikeeveryday #exceptwhensick
My BFF. #vermontlife #homesteading #woodstove #shesthebest

Unprecedented pic of all four Frugalwoodses thanks to a fellow mom who saw me trying to selfie us (while on skis) and kindly offered to snap away. Take photos of other people; they will be grateful. #skitheeast #vermontbyvermonters

March snow brings… April skiing??? Currently enjoying our second snowstorm of the week, but I’ll take it. Went on a snowshoe hike this morning; snow was so deep I thought I was going to get stuck. Thankfully did not get stuck and am now reading next to the wood stove. It’s a very Vermont-y situation. #lovermont #marchsnow #notsurprised

My backyard as seen through the fine tooth comb of the icicles hanging from the porch roof. Moments later they crashed down, reminding me of the fleeting beauty of nature. And also to never stand under snow overhangs. #themoreyouknow

Turned 39 today and it feels wonderful. I am so grateful for the life I’ve been given. Also grateful for this @misslulolabel dress I found for the wedding I went to a few weeks ago with my fellow 39-year-old hawt college buddy. As you can see, we may or may not have missed the two husbands and four children we left at home…
The snow-combovers of the woodshed, chicken coop and back porch. Who wore it best?

Quick update on how spring’s going so far. And yes, those are my children climbing onto the barn roof via a pile of snow. Pro tip: always dress your kids in fluorescent outdoor clothing. #classicvermontspring #stillsnowing

Did you know you can hire me for a one-on-one financial consultation? You can! Most of us didn’t receive personal finance education in school. Nor did we get good advice at home. And so, we launched into adulthood deeply unsure of what we’re supposed to do with our money. I get it because that used to be me.
***
Money is terrifying for a lot of people and many of us don’t know where to start. That’s where I come in. I demystify personal finance and break it down into manageable steps. I explain where to start, where to go and how to confidently manage your money on your own.
***
Want to learn more? Want to schedule a free 15-minute call with me to discuss your financial goals and challenges and how we might work together to create a holistic financial plan for your future? Follow the link in my bio!
Cannot emphasize enough how well spring is going. #vermontlife
Just a couple of spring chickens enjoying a snuggle on a snow pile. As you do. #chickencuddles #vermontbyvermonters #homesteading

Woodshed heard about the snow combover competition and upped her game. Everyone else’s fell off on account of… gravity. But Woodshed is keeping it real. No toupees here. #woodshed #snowcombover #vermontbyvermonters

Costume day at skiing: what could be better? I ended up wearing the yellow tutu by the end of the day after Kidwoods declared it an encumbrance. Received many compliments, so I think she was missing out… #stillwinter #incaseyouwerewondering #vermontlife
The stunning privilege of my daily hike through our woods. #stillwinter #vermontbyvermonters

Happy Easter from all four Frugalwoodses! This photo brought to you because I remembered to ask my fellow choir member to take it BEFORE church. Some of us were not quite so put together after service. Speaking for myself of course.
Our resident pond beavers are beaving with gusto. Managed to fell this tree right across my hiking path. Rude.

“I would like to tell you I’ve never thought about getting botox, but that would be a lie.” This month I’m reflecting on my nine years of writing Frugalwoods by revisiting some old classics. I tackled my 2015 “Frugal Beauty Manifesto” and when I wrote it, I was 31 and didn’t have any kids. Re-reading it now–at 39 with two young children–my thoughts have changed. Come see what I’ve learned at the link in my bio. Also, Littlewoods took this photo of me. I may need to hire her to do headshots… I will tell you that if you hand a 5-year-old your phone, they are willing to take THOUSANDS of pictures of you. The trade-off is that your head will be cut off in 50% of them.
The best way to do mud season

Ok I was going to say something about Adelaide’s regal walking style, but when I typed “chicken” it then suggested “nuggets.” Read the room, iPhone, read the room. #chickensofinstagram #vermontbyvermonters #happyhens

The snow melted so we immediately ran outside and started all of our garden seeds! Littlewoods planted her own tray of tomatoes, peppers, cucumbers, snap peas and ground cherries. Kidwoods began a garden journal and planted three trays of the above plus pumpkins, squash, sunflowers and beans. I planted a few trays too just for safety’s sake… something’s bound to germinate. #gardeningwithkids #vermontbyvermonters
When there’s just enough grass to run barefoot between snow piles. #vermontkids
Hard to believe this chicken is now enormous and this child is nearly in kindergarten

All hail my nine winter-surviving, hardy, recalcitrant, loud hens. I remind them daily of their tasks: 1) don’t get eaten; 2) lay an egg every now and then. They seem to be internalizing this. #chickenpeptalk
My fearless, semi-feral children. I love them so. Not so much the tree bark and detritus they bring into my house. But, worth it on balance. #vermontkids #rurallife #outsideallthetime
Water finds a way, featuring: the impromptu creek that bisects my hiking trail every spring. Where water wants to go? She goes. #hikeeveryday
When just enough snow has melted and you’ve just mastered jump roping: this is the obvious outcome. #vermontkids #rurallife

I’m fairly certain no one’s ever been so excited to help clean out a chicken coop. This kid worked for hours by my side: shoveling, raking, wheelbarrow-ing, composting. There’s nothing quite like the first spring coop clean out. And nothing like the work ethic of a preschooler. #vermontkids #homesteading

My office for the day. Many thanks to the client I just met with who did not mind the clucking chickens in the background, nor the chipmunk loudly munching a nut just off-screen. You too can talk to me in this paradise, via video. Book me at the link in my bio. Chipmunk crunching not guaranteed. #springatlast #onlyneedonesweatshirt #balmy #vermontlife

I still have depression and anxiety! May is Mental Health Awareness month and April marked the ninth anniversary of Frugalwoods, so it feels like the perfect time to reflect on my 2018 post, “How A Diagnosis Of Postpartum Depression Changed My Life.” Some things I’ve learned these past five years: Depression and anxiety are not personality traits! Taking an SSRI every day does not make me feel high or like a zombie—it makes me feel normal! Depression and anxiety are very common and nothing to be embarrassed about! Exercise, sleep, good food, close relationships, fulfilling work and a religious community all help me to feel great, but they are NOT replacements for medication and therapy! More of my journey at the link in my bio. #mentalhealthawarenessmonth #stopthestigma

social_posts.post_text: Current flower roll call! Hyacinths and daffodils are always the first—after the crocus, of course. So grateful for this burst into a new season!

The large equipment auction's free preview = GOLDEN children's entertainment. This is the second year in a row we've made a point of strolling the local auction field filled with ancient tractors, school buses, bulldozers, steamrollers, back-hoes and stuff I don't even know the name of. The girls love sitting in the cabs pretending to drive and Littlewoods declared that she wants to be a back-hoe operator when she grows up. #ruralkids

Happy Mother’s Day to all moms and mom-type folks! I’m so grateful for my mom, my mother-in-law, my sister, my sisters in law, my daughters and all the mom-like figures in my life. I love you all so very much!
Decided to plant her own flower bed this year. Weeded it, sowed the seeds, watered. Is now impatient for it to bloom. Classic gardener.
Plum blossoms in full bloom! TBD if we get to eat any plums this year… the Clever Varmint Patrol (CVP) usually culls them at the precise moment they ripen. #vermontbyvermonters
“Take a picture with me, mama!” May we have many more decades of this request. #mominthepicture
In my favorite place with my favorite people
Our glorious apple blossoms! May these flowers perform their annual miracle of transmuting into fruit. Nature, she’s magical. #vermontlife #appletrees
Happy 15th anniversary to me and this guy!!! 10 out of 10: would marry again. And yes, a REAL photographer took this picture!!! 📸 by the fabulous @maxgrudz

Thank you to everyone who reached out to see if we weathered the recent Vermont floods! I deeply appreciate your concern. We are exceedingly fortunate that our house and barn are dry and completely fine. Even the chickens made it through unscathed (despite being mad wet hens). Our quarter-mile long driveway, on the other hand, was not so lucky. The pounding, persistent rain carved unfathomably deep and wide crevices into both sides of the driveway, making it nearly impassable. We scooted down by straddling the ravines with our tires and partially driving in the woods. Yep, that’s the kids standing inside one of the crevices. Not great! We are so thankful that we have the financial resources to pay for an excavator to rebuild our driveway—a profound expense. However, many of our neighbors here in rural Vermont do not have the resources to repair the extensive damage these floods wreaked on homes, barns, bridges, businesses, driveways and fields. If you’d like to help the flood relief efforts here in Vermont, you can make a donation to The Vermont Community Foundation’s Flood Response & Recovery Fund via the link in my bio. Thank you all for your support and concern!

Delightful surprise visitors appeared in our yard the other morning: eight adorable cows! They’d jumped our neighbor’s fence, made a mad dash down our driveway and—upon spying our front lawn—ambled over and began munching the grass. We sent up the missing cow bat signal (a real thing here in rural VT) and, within an hour, the owner came to collect them. The kids were sad to see them go and have started a lobbying campaign for pet cows. Not gonna happen. #rurallife #vermontbyvermonters

I’m committed to learning new things. Even small things, such as how to bake this pie. I learned to make my own pie crusts a few years ago and, this summer, I tackled a top crust. Mistakes were made: I forgot to brush it with egg whites, so it never turned golden brown. I did not put enough filling in, so it looked kinda shrunken. But the cookie cutter stars totally worked 🌟! Best of all, I modeled being a beginner for my little beginners, who gobbled that lesson right up. #beginnermindset #piefromscratch @kingarthurbaking

Nothing like peonies from the garden that outsize your head. Will never forgot that Littlewoods called them “pee-on-me’s” for a solid two years. Also, this is from like two months ago—fear not, we don’t have mutant August-blooming peonies. #vermontbyvermonters #homesteading

Currants on their annual summer migration from berry to jam. Our currant bushes are perhaps the happiest of all our perennial foods. They thrive in rain, in heat; through it all, they burst with bounty. #homesteading #vermontbyvermonters
A few little fairy toadstools from this morning’s hike 🍄

Text from my husband, “If you want some farm-like photos, I’m currently making sparks.” Sharpening the box blade on the tractor does indeed make for some good farm-like photos. He knows me well. #homesteading #vermont #tractorlife
Nothing like shoveling compost with your sister while standing inside the compost bin (their idea, not mine 🤣). #homesteadingwithkids #vermontbyvermonters

School started two days ago so naturally now’s the time for me to replay our summer woods adventures. These two are hardy hikers, excellent gnome home builders and expert at jumping into every single creek, stream and puddle we pass. I love their love of the woods. I also love that they’re now in school so I can indulge such nostalgia. #hikingwithkids #woodslife #vermontbyvermonters

It’s the most wonderful time of the year! Felling trees, bucking logs, splitting wood and stacking it in the woodshed can only mean one thing: FALL IS HERE! I’m ready for fires in the wood stove, but since it is 70 degrees outside I suppose I can wait. Grateful to this wonderful husband of mine for all of his woodland skills and hard work! #woodshed #homesteading #vermontlife

I let Kidwoods go into debt (to me) for an inflatable fair unicorn. Last weekend was ye olde county fair here in Vermont and, of course, we were on the scene to cuddle cows (if you’re Kidwoods) and look askance at cows (if you’re Littlewoods). The county fair also provides a panorama of consumerism. So much to buy, so little time! Annoying, but a fantastic opportunity to practice money management with our children, currently clocking in at ages 5 and 7. 
🦄 🦄 🦄
Lucky for us, the county fair isn’t the only venue where we’ve been able to broach the thrilling topic of money with our kids lately:
🎁Museum gift shops: WHY DO THESE EXIST???
📚The Scholastic Book Fair: again, WHY?!?
🎡The County Fair: I’m less outraged at this one, but still mildly annoyed 
🦄 🦄 🦄
What’s my solution to all of these kid-directed-marketing ploys? Bust out your family money philosophy! Read the rest at the link in my bio.

We squeezed in one final week of summer on our second annual trip with our dear friends to their family beach house. We frolicked in the waves, boogie boarded (adults too!), watched our friend’s dog dive and swim, went crabbing (where Littlewoods caught an EEL, of all things… ), shared meals, successfully taught them Canasta and went on endless beach walks. I’m filled with gratitude for this friendship and the incredible richness it brings to our lives. Sharing life with another family is truly doubled joy and halved sorrow. @holderleadership

Welp. The garden didn’t garden much this year. Between the excessive rain, minimal sun, various varmints and—let’s not forget—my intense neglect, we netted 4 cucumbers, 12 green beans, 1 tomato and a smattering of sunflowers. Safe to say I won’t be writing any gardening books in this lifetime 🤣. #gardenfail #homesteadingwithkids #vermontbyvermonters
We very well might be at peak leaf! Peek these leaves—they could pique your interest… I’ll see myself out. #vermontbyvermonters #vermontleaves
Tis the season as the air cools and the leaves fly!
The breathtaking beauty of fresh snow and the life-changing ability to hike in it every day. I could not love this place any more! #vermontbyvermonters #snowonsnow
Actual color of the sky as seen on my hike yesterday. It’s that unreal post-storm blue—gets me every time! #vermontbyvermonters #snowshoeing #hikeeveryday
A merry holiday and happy new year to all! I cannot make up this mist on today’s hike.

Worth waking up for. Made easier by the fact that sunrise is circa 7am in winter. But we can pretend I got up early. Let’s not mention that I’ve never once posted a summer sunrise… #vermontbyvermonters #wintersunrise
